  <!-- ── Research ── -->
  <div id="research">
    <p>
      I am a PhD student in the <span class="k k1">Divinity School</span> at the
      University of Chicago, where I work at the intersection of
      <span class="k k6">religion</span>,
      <span class="k k4">literature</span>,
      <span class="k k7">finance</span>, and
      <span class="k k9">colonial history</span>.
    </p>
    <p>
      My dissertation traces the development of
      <span class="k k7">financial logics</span> in the
      <span class="k k4">early novel</span>,
      examining how the formal and rhetorical structures of eighteenth-century fiction were
      shaped by&mdash;and in turn helped to shape&mdash;the
      <span class="k k3">theological</span> and
      <span class="k k10">philosophical</span> categories through which
      <span class="k k2">credit</span>,
      <span class="k k8">risk</span>, and
      <span class="k k7">accumulation</span> were understood.
      A central thread of this project concerns the
      <span class="k k9">processes of racialization</span> bound up with
      <span class="k k2">colonial enterprise</span>:
      how financial abstraction and racial taxonomy were mutually constituted,
      and how <span class="k k4">literary form</span> registered, contested, and
      sometimes quietly reproduced that entanglement.
    </p>
    <p>
      I am broadly interested in the history of
      <span class="k k5">economic thought</span>,
      theories of the <span class="k k4">novel</span>,
      <span class="k k1">early modern religion</span>, and the long history of
      <span class="k k2">capitalism</span> and its discontents.
    </p>
  </div>

  <!-- ── CV ── -->
  <div class="section-head" id="cv">CV</div>

  <div class="cv-group">
    <div class="cv-group-label">Education</div>
